name: Viktor Klimenko
comments: Singer, guitarist and composer known as the "Singing Cossack", who was born in a prisoner-of-war camp in Svetnavalka, Karelia, to a Ukrainian Cossack father, Savva Klimenko and a Russian mother Olga Glotova. The Klimenko family migrated to Finland in 1944. There he became a musician and appeared in several films. The Eurovision Song Contest 1965 was his first appearance outside of Finland. In 1970 Klimenko released the album "Stenka Rasin" across Europe. The album, containing Russian songs, went gold in the Finnish market—the first record to do so in Finland.

name: Kathy Kirby
comments: Singer in the 1960s, whose career was launched by Bert Ambrose. She participated in the Eurovision Song Contest in 1965 with "I Belong" and came in 2nd place. After 1967 until the early-1980s, although she still recorded and had an occasional television appearance, her popularity declined.  After a nervous breakdown, she was diagnosed with schizophrenia and became reclusive. She declared bankruptcy and lived for many years on state benefits.

name: Al Stillman
comments: Lyricist, who was inducted into the Songwriters Hall of Fame in 1982. In 1933 became a staff writer for Radio City Music Hall, a position he held for nearly 40 years.

name: Armando Manzanero
comments: Musician, singer, and composer, widely considered the premier Mexican romantic composer of the postwar era and one of the most successful composers of Latin America.

name: Sid Wayne
comments: American songwriter from New York. Much of Wayne’s best-known work was written for the musical films of Elvis Presley including G.I. Blues , Fun in Acapulco , and Paradise, Hawaiian Style . In fact, almost every Elvis film contained one or more works written by Wayne and his partner Ben Weisman . Recordings from these productions often became commercially successful singles for Elvis, establishing Wayne as one of the top songwriters of the 1960s. Wayne's work has also been recorded by Sammy Davis Jr., Merle Haggard, Johnny Mathis, Dinah Washington, and the Isley Brothers, to name a few.

name: The Partridge Family

name: Bob Merrill [US1]
comments: Born in Atlantic City and grew up in Philadelphia. He was one of the most popular songwriters in the world from the late 1940s through the early 1960s. He was inducted into the Songwriters Hall of Fame in 1987.
